        "text": "Patent: US20230348994A1\nTitle: Identification of Immune-related lncRNA Signatures with Prognostic Connotation in Multi-Cancer Setting\nAssignee: Hamad Bin Khalifa University; Sidra Medicine; Qatar Foundation\nFiling Date: 2023-04-28\nGrant Date: Not provided\nAbstract: Discloses workflows to derive immune-related lncRNA signatures by differential-expression analysis and network propagation, and to use such signatures for prognosis across multiple solid cancers. Panels and scoring methods are applied pan-cancer and within specific tumour types.\nOverlaps with paper claims: C1, C2\nTechnical overlap: The claims cover selecting lncRNAs via differential expression across cohorts and validating signatures across many tumour types, mirroring the paper's per-cancer DE and coherence-based selection that shows limited cross-cancer sharing. The application's small pan-cancer signature used for prognosis maps to the paper's pan-cancer subset analysis and cross-cancer correlation behaviour.\n\nPatent: WO2023086552A2\nTitle: lncRNA transcripts in melanomagenesis\nAssignee: The Regents of the University of California (Berkeley and San Diego)\nFiling Date: 2022-11-11\nGrant Date: Not provided\nAbstract: Claims melanoma-specific lncRNA transcripts, diagnostic panels and methods derived from tumour expression comparisons with defined thresholds. Provides panels for risk assessment and therapy selection focused on melanoma.\nOverlaps with paper claims: C1\nTechnical overlap: The specification builds fixed lncRNA panels for a single tumour type using expression-thresholded differential analysis, aligning with the paper's cancer-type specific Tr-lncRNA discovery approach. Its per-cancer paneling supports the paper's finding that most transitional lncRNA signals are specific to a cancer type with minimal sharing.\n\nPatent: CN112852969B\nTitle: Epigenetically modified lncRNA as tumour diagnosis or tumour progression prediction marker\nAssignee: Wenzhou Medical University\nFiling Date: 2021-04-19\nGrant Date: 2022-06-10\nAbstract: Identifies a broad-spectrum set of 5-hydroxymethylcytosine-modified lncRNAs that distinguish cancer from healthy controls and predict tumour progression across multiple cancers. Provides detection methods and kits.\nOverlaps with paper claims: C2\nTechnical overlap: By asserting a cross-cancer panel of lncRNA markers with coherent behaviour across tumour types, the claims validate the paper's pan-cancer subset concept. The emphasis on reproducible trends across cancers parallels the paper's observation that a small group of Tr-lncRNAs exhibit consistent transition-linked changes.\n\nPatent: CN111893190A\nTitle: Application of lncRNA XIST as a diagnostic marker for gastric cancer\nAssignee: First Hospital of China Medical University\nFiling Date: 2020-09-15\nGrant Date: Not provided\nAbstract: Uses XIST expression as a diagnostic and prognostic marker for gastric cancer and provides primer and probe sets, kits, and targeting strategies.\nOverlaps with paper claims: C2\nTechnical overlap: Independent claiming of XIST as a clinically actionable biomarker matches the paper's identification of XIST within the small pan-cancer Tr-lncRNA subset that shows coherent trends over metastatic transitions. The claimed detection modalities and disease association substantiate the paper's cross-cancer emphasis on XIST's consistent signal.\n\nPatent: US20240060071A1\nTitle: Treatment of cancer associated with dysregulated novel open reading frame products\nAssignee: Cambridge Enterprise Ltd; International Centre for Genetic Engineering and Biotechnology\nFiling Date: 2021-12-15\nGrant Date: Not provided\nAbstract: Targets cancers via novel open reading frames, including ORFs in non-canonical regions such as lncRNAs. Provides detection and treatment methods spanning multiple tumour types.\nOverlaps with paper claims: C3\nTechnical overlap: The claims leverage peptides encoded by non-canonical ORFs within lncRNAs, evidencing functional small-protein coding capacity in lncRNAs, which the paper finds enriched among Tr-lncRNAs. Its detection and therapeutic use of lncRNA-derived sORFs corroborates the paper's feature-level observation of elevated coding potential, exon complexity and transcript length.",
